\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
Over the past few years, generative models including diffusion models [] and flow models [] have emerged as the dominant paradigm in modern generative AI, demonstrating unprecedented capability in synthesizing high-fidelity visual content across various modalities []. While pre-training on large-scale datasets enables these models to capture complex data distributions, aligning them with human preference and specific downstream constraints remains a critical challenge. Recently, Reinforcement Learning (RL) based fine-tuning [] like Direct Policy Optimization (DPO) [] and Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) [] has proven effective in bridging this gap, enabling the optimization of models against reward models [] that faithfully reflect human preference.
Among these advancements, Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO) [] has stood out for its efficiency and stability.
Initially grounded in Large Language Models (LLMs) [], GRPO estimates the advantage of each sample relative to a group average under a given condition (e.g., a textual prompt), thereby eliminating the need for a complex value network and fostering a scalable, flexible framework for preference alignment.
A line of researches [] have adapted GRPO for visual generation by substituting the standard ODE solvers with SDEs to introduce stochasticity during the flow sampling process.
% Given that flow models involve costly iterative denoising to synthesize clean data,
Given that the reward can only be calculated on noise-free data obtained through costly iterative denoising,
it is crucial to maximize the utility of these hard-earned samples through comprehensive evaluation.
However, existing methods typically operate under a "Single-View" paradigm: they evaluate the generated group solely against the original forward condition.
We reinterpret this evaluation protocol as
% \textbf{a highly stochastic, one-to-many mapping from the condition space $\mathcal{C}$ to the data space $\mathcal{X}$},
\textbf{an under-specified, one-to-many mapping from the condition space $\mathcal{C}$ to the data space $\mathcal{X}$},
as shown in Fig. [] (a). This formulation is inherently sparse and brittle, evidenced by the instability of reward rankings, as depicted in Fig. []. Specifically, it is observed that even slight perturbations to the input text condition lead to substantial shifts in the reward ranking of the generated group from a single SDE rollout.
% , a phenomenon that remains consistent across multiple reward models.
Such phenomenon remains consistent across multiple reward models.
This can be attributed to the high semantic density possessed by visual samples, which is difficult to validly interpret via a single condition descriptor. Consequently, relying exclusively on the initial, single condition for advantage estimation fails to capture the fine-grained relationships and intrinsic quality nuances among the generated samples, resulting in insufficient and unstable exploration.
In light of these issues, we posit that a better GRPO paradigm necessitates a shift from sparse, single-view supervision to a dense, multi-view one. Since the condition space $\mathcal{C}$ essentially forms a continuous semantic manifold, we can effectively densify the condition-data reward signal by sampling a cluster of semantically adjacent descriptors around the original condition anchor. By utilizing this augmented set of conditions to jointly evaluate the same generated group, a dense mapping can be created to offer a more comprehensive understanding of the relative advantages among samples, as illustrated in Fig. [] (b).
Based on the above analysis, we propose \textbf{M}ulti-\textbf{V}iew \textbf{GRPO} (\textbf{MV-GRPO}), a novel reinforcement learning framework that instantiates this dense supervision paradigm via an Augmented Condition Space.
% Specifically, MV-GRPO integrates a pre-trained Vision-Language Model as an \textbf{Inverse Operator} into the training loop. For each generated group, the inverse operator projects the sampled images back onto the condition manifold to retrieve a set of posterior descriptors.
Specifically, MV-GRPO introduces a flexible \textbf{Condition Enhancer} module that can be implemented in two complementary modes: (1) an online \textit{Vision-Language Model (VLM)} that projects generated images back onto the condition manifold to retrieve posterior descriptors, and (2) an offline \textit{Large Language Model (LLM)} that expands the prior condition space via semantic rewriting.
These augmented descriptors, along with the original condition, form a multi-view condition cluster used to jointly evaluate the relative advantage relationships among the generated samples. Our paradigm offers two key benefits: (i) First, the multi-view evaluation mitigates the brittleness of single-condition assessments, providing a comprehensive consensus that stabilizes the optimization process. (ii) Second, by augmenting the condition space $\mathcal{C}$ rather than the computationally expensive data space $\mathcal{X}$, our method also serves as a sample diversity booster with negligible overhead. Extensive experiments demonstrate that MV-GRPO significantly outperforms standard single-view baselines, achieving superior convergence stability and generalization capabilities on both in-domain metrics and out-of-domain benchmarks. Our contribution can be summarized as follows:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Dense Multi-View Mapping}: We identify the sparsity and brittleness of the "Single-View" evaluation in GRPO for flow models and propose a dense, multi-view supervision paradigm via augmenting the condition space.
    \item \textbf{MV-GRPO}: We present MV-GRPO, a novel GRPO framework that leverages an online/offline Condition Enhancer to construct an augmented condition manifold, establishing a multi-view consensus that effectively enhances the policy optimization and alignment performance.
    \item \textbf{Superior Performance}: MV-GRPO achieves superior performance over existing baselines, excelling in both in-domain and out-of-domain evaluation.
\end{enumerate}
\section{Related Work}
\subsection{Diffusion and Flow Matching}
Diffusion models [] have achieved exceptional performance in generative modeling by learning to reverse a gradual noising process [], enabling high-fidelity visual synthesis across various modalities []. The introduction of Latent Diffusion Models (LDMs) [] further reduces the computational cost by performing the diffusion process in a compressed latent space. Instead of simulating a stochastic diffusion path, flow models [] directly learns a continuous-time velocity field that moving along straight lines between the noise and data distributions, offering better stability and scalability, and giving rise to numerous state-of-the-art generative models [] like Flux series [], HunyuanVideo [] and WAN series [].
\subsection{Alignment for Diffusion and Flow Models}
Aligning Diffusion and Flow models with human preferences has evolved
from early PPO-style policy gradients [] and DPO variants [] toward more
efficient online reinforcement learning frameworks like Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO)[].
To enable GRPO to Flow Matching, foundational works such as Flow-GRPO [] and DanceGRPO []
reformulate deterministic Ordinary Differential Equation (ODE) sampling into equivalent Stochastic Differential Equation (SDE) trajectories,
facilitating the stochastic exploration necessary for policy optimization while preserving marginal probability distributions.
Building upon this,
several variants have emerged to refine the alignment process:
TempFlow-GRPO [] and Granular-GRPO [] introduces dense credit assignment for precise T2I alignment.
Then, efficiency is further addressed by MixGRPO [] through a hybrid ODE-SDE sampling
mechanism and by BranchGRPO [] via structured branching rollouts.
DiffusionNFT [] optimizes the forward process directly via flow matching,
defining an implicit policy direction by contrasting positive and negative generations.
Despite these advancements,
existing frameworks typically follow an under-specified,
one-to-many mapping from condition to data space via SDE rollouts,
leading to insufficient and unstable exploration. \textcolor{red}{About Our Method}
\section{Method}
% In this section, we first outline the fundamental principles and training paradigm of flow-based GRPO. Then, we revisit the reward evaluation mechanism within the standard GRPO, analyzing its limitations and highlighting the potential benefits of joint multi-condition assessment. Subsequently, we elaborate on the proposed MV-GRPO framework, which facilitates a comprehensive evaluation by leveraging an efficient online/offline Condition Enhancer.
\subsection{Preliminary: Flow-based GRPO}
\textbf{Flow Matching as MDP}.
Flow-based GRPO [] formulates the generation process as a multi-step Markov Decision Process (MDP).
% Given a condition $\mathbf{c}\in\mathcal{C}$ (e.g., a text prompt), the agent $p_\theta$ produces a reverse-time trajectory $\Gamma = (\mathbf{s}_T, \mathbf{a}_T, \dots, \mathbf{s}_0, \mathbf{a}_0)$, where the state at timestep $t$ is $\mathbf{s}_t = (\mathbf{c}, t, \mathbf{x}_t)$ and $\mathbf{x}_t$ denotes the noisy sample. Starting from $\mathbf{x}_T \sim \mathcal{N}(0, I)$, the process aims to reach the clean image $\mathbf{x}_0$. The action $\mathbf{a}_t$ stands for the single-step denoising update governed by the policy $\pi_\theta(\mathbf{x}_{t-1} | \mathbf{x}_t, \mathbf{c})$.
Let $\mathbf{c} \in \mathcal{C}$ be the condition. The agent $p_\theta$, parameterized by $\theta$, facilitates a reverse-time generation trajectory $\Gamma = (\mathbf{s}_T, \mathbf{a}_T, \dots, \mathbf{s}_0, \mathbf{a}_0)$. Here, the state $\mathbf{s}_t = (\mathbf{c}, t, \mathbf{x}_t)$ encompasses the current noisy latent $\mathbf{x}_t$ at timestep $t$, initializing from $\mathbf{x}_T \sim \mathcal{N}(0, I)$ and terminating at the clean sample $\mathbf{x}_0$. The action $\mathbf{a}_t$ corresponds to the single-step denoising update derived from the policy $\pi_\theta(\mathbf{x}_{t-1} | \mathbf{x}_t, \mathbf{c})$.
\noindent\textbf{Sampling with SDE}.
% While flow matching [] utilizes a deterministic Ordinary Differential Equation (ODE) for sampling,
% GRPO requires stochasticity to generate a diverse group of samples for advantage estimation.
% The Stochastic Differential Equation (SDE) [] is adopted at each timestep
% to inject randomness while maintaining the marginal probability flow, in which the sampling dynamics are governed by:
% \begin{equation}
%     d\mathbf{x}_t = \left(\boldsymbol{v}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c}) + \frac{\sigma_t^2}{2t}\Big(\mathbf{x}_t + (1-t)\boldsymbol{v}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c})\Big)\right)dt + \sigma_t d\mathbf{w}_t,
%     \label{eq:sde_sampling}
% \end{equation}
% where $\boldsymbol{v}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c})$ is the velocity field predicted by the model, and $\sigma_t$ controls the noise level injected via the Wiener process $d\mathbf{w}_t$.
Standard flow matching models [] typically utilize a deterministic Ordinary Differential Equation (ODE) for sampling:
\begin{equation}
    d\mathbf{x}_t = \boldsymbol{v}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c})dt,
    \label{eq:ode}
\end{equation}
where $\boldsymbol{v}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c})$ is the predicted flow velocity. To satisfy the stochastic exploration requirements of GRPO, prior works [] substitute the ODE with a Stochastic Differential Equation (SDE) that preserves the marginal distribution:
\begin{equation}
    d\mathbf{x}_t = \left(\boldsymbol{v}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c}) + \frac{\sigma_t^2}{2t}(\mathbf{x}_t + (1-t)\boldsymbol{v}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c}))\right)dt + \sigma_t d\mathbf{w}_t,
    \label{eq:sde}
\end{equation}
% where $d\mathbf{w}_t$ denotes the Wiener process increments and $\sigma_t = \eta \sqrt{\frac{t}{1-t}}$ controls the injected stochasticity governed by the hyperparameter $\eta$.
where $d\mathbf{w}_t$ represents the Wiener process increments. The term $\sigma_t = \eta \sqrt{\frac{t}{1-t}}$ modulates the magnitude of injected noise, governed by the hyperparameter $\eta$.
For practical implementation, this is discretized via the Euler-Maruyama scheme:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{x}_{t+\Delta t} = \mathbf{x}_t + \left(\boldsymbol{v}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c}) + \frac{\sigma_t^2}{2t}(\mathbf{x}_t + (1-t)\boldsymbol{v}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c}))\right)\Delta t + \sigma_t \sqrt{\Delta t} \boldsymbol{\epsilon}, \quad \boldsymbol{\epsilon} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, I).
    \label{eq:discretization}
\end{equation}
\noindent\textbf{Training of GRPO}. For a given condition $\mathbf{c}$, a group of $G$ outputs $\{\mathbf{x}_0^i\}_{i=1}^G$ is generated via the SDE solver. Then, each sample is evaluated by a reward model $R(\mathbf{x}_0^i, \mathbf{c})$, under the same condition $\mathbf{c}$. These reward scores are further standardized against the group statistics to obtain the advantage $A_i$:
\begin{equation}
    A_i = \frac{R(\mathbf{x}_0^i, \mathbf{c}) - \text{mean}(\{R(\mathbf{x}_0^j, \mathbf{c})\}_{j=1}^G)}{\text{std}(\{R(\mathbf{x}_0^j, \mathbf{c})\}_{j=1}^G)}.
    \label{eq:advantage}
\end{equation}
The objective is to maximize the PPO-style surrogate gain constrained by a KL divergence term:
\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{J}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{\mathbf{c} \sim \mathcal{C}, \{\mathbf{x}^i\} \sim \pi_{\theta_{\text{old}}}(\cdot|\mathbf{c})} \left[ \frac{1}{G} \sum_{i=1}^G \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=0}^{T-1} \mathcal{L}_{\text{clip}}(r_t^i, A_i) - \beta D_{\text{KL}}(\pi_\theta \| \pi_{\text{ref}}) \right],
    \label{eq:objective}
\end{equation}
where:
\begin{equation}
     \mathcal{L}_{\text{clip}}(r_t^i, A_i) = \min \left( r_t^i(\theta)A_i, \text{clip}(r_t^i(\theta), 1-\varepsilon, 1+\varepsilon)A_i \right),
    \label{eq:loss_function}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
r_t^i(\theta) = \frac{p_\theta(\mathbf{x}_{t-1}^i | \mathbf{x}_t^i, \mathbf{c})}{p_{\theta_{\text{old}}}(\mathbf{x}_{t-1}^i | \mathbf{x}_t^i, \mathbf{c})}.
\label{eq:ratio}
\end{equation}
The coefficient $\beta$ in Eq.~\ref{eq:objective} balances the KL regularization during training.
% , which is typically set to 0 [] for stability in training.
\subsection{Observation and Analysis}
Since Flow-based GRPO relies on time-consuming iterative denoising to synthesize visual samples, it is imperative to perform a robust and thorough assessment to fully exploit their value. Nevertheless, through careful investigation, we reveal that the reward evaluation employed in current flow-based GRPO methods [] is sparse and brittle. In particular, it is observed that the reward ranking within a generated group is highly sensitive to the input condition.
As depicted in Fig. [], slight perturbations to the condition $\mathbf{c}$ (e.g., \texttt{addition}, \texttt{deletion} and \texttt{synonymous rewriting}) frequently trigger substantial shifts in the relative ordering of $\{R(\mathbf{x}_0^i, \mathbf{c})\}_{i=1}^G$, while the images themselves remain static. Given a perturbed condition $\mathbf{c}'\in\mathcal{C}$, such phenomenon can be formulated as:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:perturbation}
    \texttt{argsort}_iR(\mathbf{x}_0^i, \mathbf{c}) \neq \texttt{argsort}_iR(\mathbf{x}_0^i, \mathbf{c}'),
\end{equation}
According to Eq. \ref{eq:advantage}, the relative advantage $A_i$ of a sample $\mathbf{x}_0^i$ within its group is determined by the statistical distribution of intra-group rewards. This implies that a sample $\mathbf{x}_0^i$ could be deemed "positive" ($A_i > 0$) under view $\mathbf{c}$ but "negative" ($A_i < 0$) under a semantically similar view $\mathbf{c}'$, thereby undermining the stability and completeness of standard single-condition evaluation.
\subsection{Condition Enhancer}
To facilitate a comprehensive evaluation of visual samples, we consider sampling auxiliary descriptors from the local manifold surrounding the anchor condition $\mathbf{c}$ in the continuous space $\mathcal{C}$ for a dense multi-view assessment. We formalize the Condition Enhancer operator as $\mathcal{E}: \mathcal{C} \times \mathcal{X} \to 2^\mathcal{C}$, which maps an anchor condition $\mathbf{c}$ and a sample group $\mathbf{X}_G = \{\mathbf{x}_0^i\}_{i=1}^G$ to an augmented condition set:
\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{V}_K = \mathcal{E}(\mathbf{c}, \mathbf{X}_G) = \left\{ \mathbf{c}' \in \mathcal{C} \mid \mathbf{c}' \sim p_\mathcal{E}(\cdot | \mathbf{c}, \mathbf{X}_G) \right\},
    \label{eq:operator_mapping}
\end{equation}
in which $\mathcal{V}_K$ denotes the resulting augmented condition set containing $K$ additional views, and $p_\mathcal{E}$ represents the sampling distribution of $\mathcal{E}$ given $\mathbf{c}$ and $\mathbf{X}_G$. In practical, we provide two complementary implementations of $\mathcal{E}$:
\noindent\textbf{Online VLM Enhancer}. To dynamically capture the visual semantics of generated samples, a pretrained Vision-Language Model (VLM) is employed as an online Condition Enhancer $\mathcal{E}_\text{VLM}$. During the training loop, $\mathcal{E}_\text{VLM}$ projects each sample $\mathbf{x}_0^i \in \mathbf{X}_G$ back to the condition space to obtain posterior descriptors:
% \begin{equation}\label{eq:vlm_enhance}
%     \mathbf{c}_i^{\text{post}} \sim p_{\mathcal{E}_\text{VLM}}(\cdot | \mathbf{c}, \mathbf{x}_0^i, \texttt{P}_\text{VLM}), \quad \mathbf{c},\mathbf{c}_i^{\text{post}}\in\mathcal{C}, \quad \forall i \in \{1, \dots, G\},
% \end{equation}
\begin{equation}\label{eq:vlm_enhance}
    \mathcal{V}^{\text{post}}_G = \left\{ \mathbf{c}_i^{\text{post}} \in \mathcal{C} \mid \mathbf{c}_i^{\text{post}} \sim p_{\mathcal{E}_\text{VLM}}(\cdot | \mathbf{c}, \mathbf{x}_0^i, \texttt{P}_\text{VLM}), \forall \mathbf{x}_0^i \in \mathbf{X}_G \right\},
\end{equation}
where the prompt $\texttt{P}_\text{VLM}$ instructs $\mathcal{E}_\text{VLM}$ to describe visual contents within $\mathbf{x}_0^i$. For each enhancement given by Eq.~\ref{eq:vlm_enhance}, $\texttt{P}_\text{VLM}$ is randomly sampled from a instruction set $\mathcal{P}_\text{VLM}$ covering diverse descriptive perspectives (e.g., \texttt{lighting}, \texttt{composition}, \texttt{style}, etc.). The above design guarantees the diversity of augmented conditions from two aspects: (i) First, each $\mathbf{c}_i^{\text{post}}$ is derived from a unique SDE sample $\mathbf{x}_0^i \in \mathbf{X}_G$; (ii) Second, $\mathcal{E}_\text{VLM}$ is queried with varied instructions $\texttt{P}_\text{VLM} \in \mathcal{P}_\text{VLM}$ focusing on different attributes.
\noindent\textbf{Offline LLM Enhancer}. For efficient condition augmentation, a pretrained Large Language Model (LLM) is utilized as an offline Condition Enhancer $\mathcal{E}_\text{LLM}$, which directly samples prior descriptors given the anchor condition $\mathbf{c}$:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:llm_enhance}
    \mathcal{V}^{\text{prior}}_G = \left\{ \mathbf{c}_j^{\text{prior}} \in \mathcal{C} \mid \mathbf{c}_j^{\text{prior}} \sim p_{\mathcal{E}_\text{LLM}}(\cdot | \mathbf{c}, \texttt{Mem}, \texttt{P}_\text{LLM}), j=1 \dots G \right\},
\end{equation}
where the prompt $\texttt{P}_\text{LLM}$ instructs $\mathcal{E}_\text{LLM}$ to rewrite the condition. Mirroring the online mode to ensure diversity, (i) $\texttt{Mem}$ represents a historical output buffer introduced to prevent duplicate responses, and (ii) $\texttt{P}_\text{LLM}$ is randomly chose from an editing prompt set $\mathcal{P}_\text{LLM}$, which includes three operations: \texttt{addition}, \texttt{deletion}, and \texttt{substitution}. Crucially, since $\mathcal{E}_\text{LLM}$ operates independently of image generation, it can be executed entirely offline before training.
\subsection{Multi-View GRPO}
Building upon the above analysis of dense condition-data mapping, we propose MV-GRPO, a multi-view flow-based GRPO framework  designed to maximize alignment stability and sample utility, as shown in Fig. [].
% Building upon
\noindent\textbf{Training Objective}. The model is fine-tuned on a mixed set of both the original condition and the augmented conditions. The final MV-GRPO objective is constructed by aggregating the policy gradient losses across the anchor view $\mathbf{c}$ and the $K$  augmented conditions in $\mathcal{V}_K$, with the KL term omitted for brevity:
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
    &\mathcal{J}_{\text{MV-GRPO}}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{\mathbf{c} \sim \mathcal{C}, \{\mathbf{x}_0^i\}_{i=1}^{G} \sim \pi_{\theta_{\text{old}}}(\cdot|\mathbf{c}), \textcolor{blue}{\{\mathbf{c}_k\}_{k=1}^K\sim p_{\mathcal{E}}(\cdot | \mathbf{c}, \mathbf{X}_G)}} \\
    &\Bigg[\underbrace{ \frac{1}{G} \sum_{i=1}^G \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=0}^{T-1} \min \left( r^i_t(\theta) A_i^{\mathbf{c}}, \text{clip}(r^i_t(\theta), 1-\varepsilon, 1+\varepsilon) A_i^{\mathbf{c}} \right)}_{\text{Objective for the Original Condition}}
    + \\ & \underbrace{\sum_{k=1}^K \frac{1}{G} \sum_{i=1}^G \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=0}^{T-1} \min \left( r^{'i}_t(\theta, \mathbf{c}_k) A_i^{\mathbf{c}_k}, \text{clip}(r^{'i}_t(\theta, \mathbf{c}_k), 1-\varepsilon, 1+\varepsilon) A_i^{\mathbf{c}_k} \right) }_{\text{Objective for Augmented Conditions}}
    \Bigg],
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:mv_objective}
\end{equation}
where $A_i^{\mathbf{c}_k}$ is the advantage for the sample $\mathbf{x}_0^i$ under condition $\mathbf{c}_k$ (given by Eq.~\ref{eq:advantage}), with $r^i_t(\theta)$ and $r^{'i}_t(\theta, \mathbf{c}_k)$ denoting the importance sampling ratios conditioned on $\mathbf{c}$ and $\mathbf{c}_k$, respectively:
\begin{equation}
    r_t^i(\theta) = \frac{p_\theta(\mathbf{x}_{t-1}^i | \mathbf{x}_t^i, \mathbf{c})}{p_{\theta_{\text{old}}}(\mathbf{x}_{t-1}^i | \mathbf{x}_t^i, \mathbf{c})}, r^{'i}_t(\theta, \mathbf{c}_k) = \frac{p_\theta(\mathbf{x}_{t-1}^i | \mathbf{x}_t^i, \textcolor{blue}{\mathbf{c}_k})}{p_{\theta_{\text{old}}}(\mathbf{x}_{t-1}^i | \mathbf{x}_t^i, \mathbf{c})}.
\end{equation}
The training pipeline of MV-GRPO is detailed in Algorithm. [].
