\noindent\textbf{Theoretical Perspective}.
While MV-GRPO evaluates samples using augmented conditions $\mathbf{c}' \in \mathcal{V}_K$, the trajectories $\{\mathbf{x}_0^i\}$ are physically generated via the SDE solver conditioned on the anchor $\mathbf{c}$. To justify the optimization of $\pi_\theta(\cdot|\mathbf{c}')$ using off-policy samples from $\pi_{\text{old}}(\cdot|\mathbf{c})$, we must quantify the probability of observing the original trajectory steps under the augmented view.

Consider a single discretization step from $t$ to $t-1$ (where $t$ runs from $T$ to $1$). Based on the Euler-Maruyama scheme (Eq.~\ref{eq:discretization}), the transition kernel $p_\theta(\mathbf{x}_{t-1} | \mathbf{x}_t, \mathbf{c})$ is a Gaussian distribution:
\begin{equation}
    p_\theta(\mathbf{x}_{t-1} | \mathbf{x}_t, \mathbf{c}) = \mathcal{N}\left(\mathbf{x}_{t-1}; \boldsymbol{\mu}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c}), \Sigma_t\right),
\end{equation}
where the covariance is isotropic $\Sigma_t = \sigma_t^2 \Delta t \mathbf{I}$, and the mean is defined by the velocity field:
\begin{equation}
    \boldsymbol{\mu}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c}) = \mathbf{x}_t + \left(\boldsymbol{v}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c}) + \frac{\sigma_t^2}{2t}(\mathbf{x}_t + (1-t)\boldsymbol{v}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c}))\right)\Delta t.
\end{equation}
During the forward sampling with the anchor $\mathbf{c}$, the realized next state $\mathbf{x}_{t-1}$ is obtained via a specific noise realization $\boldsymbol{\epsilon} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \mathbf{I})$:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{x}_{t-1} = \boldsymbol{\mu}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c}) + \sigma_t \sqrt{\Delta t} \boldsymbol{\epsilon}.
    \label{eq:realized_sample}
\end{equation}
When evaluating this transition under an augmented condition $\mathbf{c}'$, the distribution shifts to $\mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{\mu}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c}'), \Sigma_t)$. The probability density of the \textit{original} sample $\mathbf{x}_{t-1}$ under this \textit{new} condition is determined by the semantic alignment of the velocity fields. We can reformulate $\mathbf{x}_{t-1}$ as a sample from the augmented distribution with an \textbf{equivalent noise shift} $\boldsymbol{\epsilon}'$:
\begin{equation}
    \boldsymbol{\epsilon}' = \boldsymbol{\epsilon} + \underbrace{\frac{\boldsymbol{\mu}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c}) - \boldsymbol{\mu}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t, \mathbf{c}')}{\sigma_t \sqrt{\Delta t}}}_{\text{Semantic Drift}},
\end{equation}
Consequently, the log-probability of sampling the original trajectory point $\mathbf{x}_{t-1}$ under the augmented condition $\mathbf{c}'$ is given by:
\begin{equation}
    \log p_\theta(\mathbf{x}_{t-1} | \mathbf{x}_t, \mathbf{c}') \propto - \frac{1}{2} \| \boldsymbol{\epsilon}' \|^2 = - \frac{1}{2} \left\| \boldsymbol{\epsilon} + \frac{\Delta \boldsymbol{\mu}(\mathbf{c}, \mathbf{c}')}{\sigma_t \sqrt{\Delta t}} \right\|^2.
\end{equation}
This derivation highlights two critical insights for MV-GRPO: (1) The importance sampling ratio $r^{'i}_t(\theta, \mathbf{c}_k)$ in Eq.~\ref{eq:mv_objective} is mathematically well-defined as long as the augmented conditions lie within a local semantic neighborhood where the velocity difference $\Delta \boldsymbol{\mu}$ is bounded. (2) By maximizing the objective under $\mathbf{c}'$, the model is encouraged to align the velocity field $\boldsymbol{v}_\theta(\cdot, \mathbf{c}')$ such that the "Semantic Drift" is minimized for high-reward samples, effectively enforcing a multi-view consensus on the optimal generation path.
